SMU Confess
#love‚ù§Ô∏è

Nothing wrong with marrying a rich guy. But if you approach with shallow intentions, make sure you remain attractive to him past your prime or he may dump you like people dump escorts. There's going to be way younger, fresher competition vying to take your place, and your confidence and overall mental wellbeing may take a hit. Your quality of life will jump quickly, but maintaining a high quality of life will be dependent on him. That's the unfortunate problem with an unequal power dynamic.

If you marry someone that isn't rich, your quality of life will improve slowly, but he'll know you like him for himself. It's a more healthy relationship, and both are more likely to respect one another's opinions and decisions. But there's no guarantee that you'll be well-off in the end.

There's pros and cons of both lah. No need to hate on those that want a better quality of life, and no need to bash those that want a more normal relationship.

i think it depends on ur overall financial situation but a good rule of thumb is that discretionary spending should be a small percentage of your net worth or annual income to avoid financial strain. 500k annual income will be around 4 percent or less, which makes 20k reasonable if expenses are well managed. 250k annual income and below 20k becomes a significant chunk. for the average singaporean the salary is around 60k to 80k per annum. 3k to 5k will be okay per year for a luxury trip or major gift. all i can say is spend within ur means, love isnt measured in dollars.

What Are the Chances of Meeting a 20-35-Year-Old Man in Singapore Earning $500K+?

Let‚Äôs break it down. Singapore has around 3.6 million residents, with 400K-450K men aged 20-35. Now, only the top 0.1-0.2% of earners in this age group make SGD 500K+ annually, which translates to just 400 to 900 men in the entire country.

Now, let‚Äôs factor in relationships. Since high earners tend to be in relationships, about 20-30% of them are single, meaning only 80 to 270 single men in this bracket exist.

So, what are your actual chances of meeting one?
Against the total Singaporean population (3.6M), it‚Äôs 0.002-0.007%. Against all men aged 20-35 (400K-450K), it‚Äôs 0.02-0.06%.

That's is like 1 in 15,000 to 45,000 people.

Basically, meeting one is like finding a rare Pok√©mon in the wild. üòÜ

#random‚ú®

Paying for a job position is a serious crime, specifically bribery. If caught, you will face severe legal consequences, including imprisonment. A 10-year jail sentence for bribery charges is a significant punishment, reflecting the gravity of the offense.

The consequences extend beyond the legal realm. Your reputation will be permanently tarnished. Everyone will know you were convicted of bribery to secure a position at a company, a company now associated with your criminal actions. This public knowledge will lead to lasting shame and social stigma.

The emotional toll of such actions is immense. Spending a decade in jail, knowing your actions were illegal and unethical, will likely lead to profound regret. The experience can be emotionally devastating, potentially causing daily suffering and remorse. The shame and the loss of freedom will be a constant burden.

Drinking alcohol can have several negative effects on your health, both in the short term and long term.

Short-Term Effects

Increased Risk of Accidents: This impairment can result in accidents, such as falls, drownings, and motor vehicle crashes
Alcohol Poisoning: Consuming large amounts of alcohol in a short period can lead to alcohol poisoning, which can be life-threatening

Long-Term Effects

Liver Damage: Chronic alcohol consumption can lead to liver diseases such as fatty liver, alcoholic hepatitis, fibrosis, and cirrhosis
